The Governor of Ondo State, Oluwarotimi Akeredolu has described the late former Governor of old Ondo State, Evangelist Bamidele Olumilua as a great mind who injected a lot of thinking into governance during his tenure. According to Akeredolu in a message issued on Thursday while commiserating with the people of Ekiti State over the passing of the ex-governor, he said Olumilua lived an exemplary life worthy of emulation by the younger generation. DAILY POST had on Thursday reported the demise of Olumilua who died at the age of 80 in his country home of Ikere-Ekiti, Ekiti State. In a statement issued by the Governor’s Chief Press Secretary, Segun Ajiboye, he stated that with the death of Olumilua, the generation of politicians who believe that politics and governance are about service to the people were gradually diminishing. The statement reads in parts, “According to the governor, Olumilua lived a good, worthy and exemplary life from which younger generations can learn and imbibe the attributes of discipline, strong character, forthrightness, patience and hard work. “Governor Akeredolu prays that the almighty God will grant the soul of the great politician eternal rest and comfort his family, friends and political associates. “Governor Akeredolu condoles with family members, friends and political associates of the consummate politician who achieved remarkable and indelible feats as the governor of the old Ondo state from January 1992 to November 1993. “The demise of the illustrious son of Ekiti at 80 amounts to further depletion of the generation of politicians who believe that politics and governance are about service to the people.”